 3473:     Create a preprocessing pipeline for data transformation and feature engineering.
 3474: 
 3475:     Function constructs a pipeline to preprocess data for machine learning tasks,
 3476:     accommodating a variety of transformations including scaling, encoding,
 3477:     and dimensionality reduction. It supports both numerical and categorical data,
 3478:     and can incorporate custom transformations.
 3479: 
 3480:     Parameters
 3481:     ----------
 3482:     X : np.ndarray or DataFrame
 3483:         Input features dataframe or arraylike. Must be two dimensional array.
 3484:     y : array-like, optional
 3485:         Target variable. Required for supervised learning tasks.
 3486:     num_features : list of str, optional
 3487:         List of numerical feature names. If None, determined automatically.
 3488:     cat_features : list of str, optional
 3489:         List of categorical feature names. If None, determined automatically.
 3490:     custom_transformers : list of tuples, optional
 3491:         Custom transformers to be included in the pipeline. Each tuple should
 3492:         contain ('name', transformer_instance).
 3493:     label_encoding : str or transformer, default 'LabelEncoder'
 3494:         Encoder for the target variable. Accepts standard scikit-learn encoders
 3495:         or custom encoder objects.
 3496:     scaler : str or transformer, default 'StandardScaler'
 3497:         Scaler for numerical features. Accepts standard scikit-learn scalers
 3498:         or custom scaler objects.
 3499:     missing_values : int, float, str, np.nan, None, default np.nan
 3500:         Placeholder for missing values for imputation.
 3501:     impute_strategy : str, default 'median'
 3502:         Imputation strategy. Options: 'mean', 'median', 'most_frequent', 'constant'.
 3503:     feature_interaction : bool, default False
 3504:         If True, generate polynomial and interaction features.
 3505:     dimension_reduction : str or transformer, optional
 3506:         Dimensionality reduction technique. Accepts 'PCA', 't-SNE', or custom object.
 3507:     feature_selection : str or transformer, optional
 3508:         Feature selection method. Accepts 'SelectKBest', 'SelectFromModel', or custom object.
 3509:     balance_classes : bool, default False
 3510:         If True, balance classes in classification tasks.
 3511:     advanced_imputation : transformer, optional
 3512:         Advanced imputation technique like KNNImputer or IterativeImputer.
 3513:     verbose : bool, default False
 3514:         Enable verbose output.
 3515:     output_format : str, default 'array'
 3516:         Desired output format: 'array' or 'dataframe'.
 3517:     transform : bool, default False
 3518:         If True, apply the pipeline to the data immediately and return transformed data.
 3519: 
 3520:     Returns
 3521:     -------
 3522:     full_pipeline : Pipeline or (X_transformed, y_transformed)
 3523:         The constructed preprocessing pipeline, or transformed data if `transform` is True.
 3524: 
 3525:     Examples
 3526:     --------
 3527:     >>> from gofast.tools.mlutils import build_data_preprocessor

static PyObject *__pyx_pw_6gofast_5tools_7mlutils_85soft_imputer(PyObject *__pyx_self, 
#if CYTHON_METH_FASTCALL
PyObject *const *__pyx_args, Py_ssize_t __pyx_nargs, PyObject *__pyx_kwds
#else

PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6gofast_5tools_7mlutils_84soft_imputer, "\n    Impute missing values in a dataset, optionally dropping features and handling \n    both numerical and categorical data.\n\n    This function extends the functionality of scikit-learn's SimpleImputer to \n    support dropping specified features and a ``bi-impute`` mode for handling \n    both numerical and categorical data. It ensures API consistency with \n    scikit-learn's transformers and allows for flexible imputation strategies.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    X : array-like or sparse matrix of shape (n_samples, n_features)\n        The input data to impute.\n        \n    strategy : str, default='mean'\n        The imputation strategy:\n        - 'mean': Impute using the mean of each column. Only for numeric data.\n        - 'median': Impute using the median of each column. Only for numeric data.\n        - 'most_frequent': Impute using the most frequent value of each column. \n          For numeric and categorical data.\n        - 'constant': Impute using the specified `fill_value`.\n        \n    missing_values : int, float, str, np.nan, None, or pd.NA, default=np.nan\n        The placeholder for the missing values. All occurrences of\n        `missing_values` will be imputed.\n        \n    fill_value : str or numerical value, default=None\n        When `strategy` == 'constant', `fill_value` is used to replace all\n        occurrences of `missing_values`. If left to the default, `fill_value` \n        will be 0 when imputing numerical data and 'missing_value' for strings \n        or object data types.\n        For 'constant' strategy, specifies the value used for replacement.\n        In 'bi-impute' mode, allows specifying separate fill values for\n        numerical and categorical data using a delimiter from the set\n        {\"__\", \"--\", \"&\", \"@\", \"!\"}. For example, \"0.5__missing\" indicates\n        0.5 as fill value for numerical data and \"missing\" for categorical.\n        \n    drop_features : bool or list, default=False""\n        If True, drops all categorical features before imputation. If a list, \n        drops specified features.\n        \n    mode : str, optional\n        If set to 'bi-impute', imputes both numerical and categorical features \n        and returns a single imputed dataframe. Only 'bi-impute' is supported.\n        \n    copy : bool, default=True\n        If True, a copy of X will be created. If False, imputation will\n        be done in-place whenever possible.\n        \n    verbose : int, default=0\n        Controls the verbosity of the imputer.\n        \n    add_indicator : bool, default=False\n        If True, a `MissingIndicator` transform will be added to the output \n        of the imputer's transform.\n        \n    keep_empty_features : bool, default=False\n        If True, features that are all missing when `fit` is called are \n        included in the transform output.\n        \n    skip_columns : list of str or int, optional\n        Specifies the columns to exclude from processing when the decorator is\n        applied to a function. If the input data `X` is a pandas DataFrame, \n        `skip_columns` should contain the names of the columns to be skipped. \n        If `X` is a numpy array, `skip_columns`  should be a list of column \n        indices (integers) indicating the positions of the columns to be excluded.\n        This allows selective processing of data, avoiding alterations to the\n        specified columns.\n        \n    **kwargs : dict\n        Additional fitting parameters.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    Xi : array-like or sparse matrix of shape (n_samples, n_features)\n        The imputed dataset.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> import numpy as np \n    >>> from gofast.tools.mlutils import soft_imputer\n    >>> X = np.array([[1, np.nan, 3], [4, 5, np.nan], [np.nan, np.nan, 9]])\n    >>> soft_imputer(X, strategy='mean')\n    array([[ 1. ,  5. ,  3. ],\n           [ 4. ,  5. ,  6. ],\n           [ 2.5,  5. ,  9. ]])\n   "" \n    >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, np.nan], 'B': ['a', np.nan, 'b']})\n    >>> soft_imputer(df, strategy='most_frequent', mode='bi-impute')\n               A  B\n        0    1.0  a\n        1    2.0  a\n        2    1.5  b\n\n    Notes\n    -----\n    The 'bi-impute' mode requires categorical features to be explicitly indicated\n    as such by using pandas Categorical dtype or by specifying features to drop.\n    ");

 3732:     **kwargs
 3733:     ):
 3734:     """
 3735:     Impute missing values in a dataset, optionally dropping features and handling
 3736:     both numerical and categorical data.
 3737: 
 3738:     This function extends the functionality of scikit-learn's SimpleImputer to
 3739:     support dropping specified features and a ``bi-impute`` mode for handling
 3740:     both numerical and categorical data. It ensures API consistency with
 3741:     scikit-learn's transformers and allows for flexible imputation strategies.
 3742: 
 3743:     Parameters
 3744:     ----------
 3745:     X : array-like or sparse matrix of shape (n_samples, n_features)
 3746:         The input data to impute.
 3747: 
 3748:     strategy : str, default='mean'
 3749:         The imputation strategy:
 3750:         - 'mean': Impute using the mean of each column. Only for numeric data.
 3751:         - 'median': Impute using the median of each column. Only for numeric data.
 3752:         - 'most_frequent': Impute using the most frequent value of each column.
 3753:           For numeric and categorical data.
 3754:         - 'constant': Impute using the specified `fill_value`.
 3755: 
 3756:     missing_values : int, float, str, np.nan, None, or pd.NA, default=np.nan
 3757:         The placeholder for the missing values. All occurrences of
 3758:         `missing_values` will be imputed.
 3759: 
 3760:     fill_value : str or numerical value, default=None
 3761:         When `strategy` == 'constant', `fill_value` is used to replace all
 3762:         occurrences of `missing_values`. If left to the default, `fill_value`
 3763:         will be 0 when imputing numerical data and 'missing_value' for strings
 3764:         or object data types.
 3765:         For 'constant' strategy, specifies the value used for replacement.
 3766:         In 'bi-impute' mode, allows specifying separate fill values for
 3767:         numerical and categorical data using a delimiter from the set
 3768:         {"__", "--", "&", "@", "!"}. For example, "0.5__missing" indicates
 3769:         0.5 as fill value for numerical data and "missing" for categorical.
 3770: 
 3771:     drop_features : bool or list, default=False
 3772:         If True, drops all categorical features before imputation. If a list,
 3773:         drops specified features.
 3774: 
 3775:     mode : str, optional
 3776:         If set to 'bi-impute', imputes both numerical and categorical features
 3777:         and returns a single imputed dataframe. Only 'bi-impute' is supported.
 3778: 
 3779:     copy : bool, default=True
 3780:         If True, a copy of X will be created. If False, imputation will
 3781:         be done in-place whenever possible.
 3782: 
 3783:     verbose : int, default=0
 3784:         Controls the verbosity of the imputer.
 3785: 
 3786:     add_indicator : bool, default=False
 3787:         If True, a `MissingIndicator` transform will be added to the output
 3788:         of the imputer's transform.
 3789: 
 3790:     keep_empty_features : bool, default=False
 3791:         If True, features that are all missing when `fit` is called are
 3792:         included in the transform output.
 3793: 
 3794:     skip_columns : list of str or int, optional
 3795:         Specifies the columns to exclude from processing when the decorator is
 3796:         applied to a function. If the input data `X` is a pandas DataFrame,
 3797:         `skip_columns` should contain the names of the columns to be skipped.
 3798:         If `X` is a numpy array, `skip_columns`  should be a list of column
 3799:         indices (integers) indicating the positions of the columns to be excluded.
 3800:         This allows selective processing of data, avoiding alterations to the
 3801:         specified columns.
 3802: 
 3803:     **kwargs : dict
 3804:         Additional fitting parameters.
 3805: 
 3806:     Returns
 3807:     -------
 3808:     Xi : array-like or sparse matrix of shape (n_samples, n_features)
 3809:         The imputed dataset.
 3810: 
 3811:     Examples
 3812:     --------
 3813:     >>> import numpy as np
 3814:     >>> from gofast.tools.mlutils import soft_imputer
 3815:     >>> X = np.array([[1, np.nan, 3], [4, 5, np.nan], [np.nan, np.nan, 9]])
 3816:     >>> soft_imputer(X, strategy='mean')
 3817:     array([[ 1. ,  5. ,  3. ],
 3818:            [ 4. ,  5. ,  6. ],
 3819:            [ 2.5,  5. ,  9. ]])
 3820: 
 3821:     >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, np.nan], 'B': ['a', np.nan, 'b']})
 3822:     >>> soft_imputer(df, strategy='most_frequent', mode='bi-impute')
 3823:                A  B
 3824:         0    1.0  a
 3825:         1    2.0  a
 3826:         2    1.5  b
 3827: 
 3828:     Notes
 3829:     -----
 3830:     The 'bi-impute' mode requires categorical features to be explicitly indicated
 3831:     as such by using pandas Categorical dtype or by specifying features to drop.
 3832:     """

One of 'StandardScaler', \n        'MinMaxScaler', 'Normalizer', or 'RobustScaler'.\n    copy : bool, default=True\n        If False, avoid a copy and perform inplace scaling instead.\n    with_mean : bool, default=True\n        If True, center the data before scaling. Only applicable when kind is\n        'StandardScaler' or 'RobustScaler'.\n    with_std : bool, default=True\n        If True, scale the data to unit variance. Only applicable when kind is\n        'StandardScaler' or 'RobustScaler'.\n    feature_range : tuple (min, max), default=(0, 1)\n        Desired range of transformed data. Only applicable when kind \n        is 'MinMaxScaler'.\n    clip : bool, default=False\n        Set to True to clip transformed values to the provided feature range.\n        Only applicable when kind is 'MinMaxScaler'.\n    norm : {'l1', 'l2', 'max'}, default='l2'\n        The norm to use to normalize each non-zero sample or feature.\n        Only applicable when kind is 'Normalizer'.\n    skip_columns : list of str or int, optional\n        Specifies the columns to exclude from processing when the decorator is\n        applied to a function. If the input data `X` is a pandas DataFrame, \n        `skip_columns` should contain the names of the columns to be skipped. \n        If `X` is a numpy array, `skip_columns`  should be a list of column \n        indices (integers) indicating the positions of the columns to be excluded.\n        This allows selective processing of data, avoiding alterations to the\n        spec""ified columns.\n    verbose : int, default=0\n        If > 0, print messages about the processing.\n        \n    **kwargs : additional keyword arguments\n        Additional fitting parameters to pass to the scaler.\n        \n    Returns\n    -------\n    X_scaled : {ndarray, sparse matrix, dataframe} of shape (n_samples, n_features)\n        The scaled data. The scaled data with numerical features scaled according\n        to the specified kind, and categorical features returned unchanged. \n        The return type matches the input type.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> import numpy as np \n    >>> import pandas as pd \n    >>> from gofast.tools.mlutils import soft_scaler\n    >>> X = np.array([[1, -1, 2], [2, 0, 0], [0, 1, -1]])\n    >>> X_scaled = soft_scaler(X, kind='StandardScaler')\n    >>> print(X_scaled)\n    [[ 0.  -1.22474487  1.33630621]\n     [ 1.22474487  0.  -0.26726124]\n     [-1.22474487  1.22474487 -1.06904497]]\n\n    >>> df = pd.DataFrame(X, columns=['a', 'b', 'c'])\n    >>> df_scaled = soft_scaler(df, kind='RobustScaler', with_centering=True,\n                                with_scaling=True)\n    >>> print(df_scaled)\n              a    b    c\n        0 -0.5 -1.0  1.0\n        1  0.5  0.0  0.0\n        2 -0.5  1.0 -1.0\n    ");

 4051:     """
 4052:     Scale data using specified scaling strategy from scikit-learn.
 4053: 
 4054:     Function excludes categorical features from scaling and provides
 4055:     feedback via verbose parameter.
 4056: 
 4057:     Parameters
 4058:     ----------
 4059:     X : DataFrame or array-like of shape (n_samples, n_features)
 4060:         The data to scale, can contain both numerical and categorical features.
 4061:     kind : str, default='StandardScaler'
 4062:         The kind of scaling to apply to numerical features. One of 'StandardScaler',
 4063:         'MinMaxScaler', 'Normalizer', or 'RobustScaler'.
 4064:     copy : bool, default=True
 4065:         If False, avoid a copy and perform inplace scaling instead.
 4066:     with_mean : bool, default=True
 4067:         If True, center the data before scaling. Only applicable when kind is
 4068:         'StandardScaler' or 'RobustScaler'.
 4069:     with_std : bool, default=True
 4070:         If True, scale the data to unit variance. Only applicable when kind is
 4071:         'StandardScaler' or 'RobustScaler'.
 4072:     feature_range : tuple (min, max), default=(0, 1)
 4073:         Desired range of transformed data. Only applicable when kind
 4074:         is 'MinMaxScaler'.
 4075:     clip : bool, default=False
 4076:         Set to True to clip transformed values to the provided feature range.
 4077:         Only applicable when kind is 'MinMaxScaler'.
 4078:     norm : {'l1', 'l2', 'max'}, default='l2'
 4079:         The norm to use to normalize each non-zero sample or feature.
 4080:         Only applicable when kind is 'Normalizer'.
 4081:     skip_columns : list of str or int, optional
 4082:         Specifies the columns to exclude from processing when the decorator is
 4083:         applied to a function. If the input data `X` is a pandas DataFrame,
 4084:         `skip_columns` should contain the names of the columns to be skipped.
 4085:         If `X` is a numpy array, `skip_columns`  should be a list of column
 4086:         indices (integers) indicating the positions of the columns to be excluded.
 4087:         This allows selective processing of data, avoiding alterations to the
 4088:         specified columns.
 4089:     verbose : int, default=0
 4090:         If > 0, print messages about the processing.
 4091: 
 4092:     **kwargs : additional keyword arguments
 4093:         Additional fitting parameters to pass to the scaler.
 4094: 
 4095:     Returns
 4096:     -------
 4097:     X_scaled : {ndarray, sparse matrix, dataframe} of shape (n_samples, n_features)
 4098:         The scaled data. The scaled data with numerical features scaled according
 4099:         to the specified kind, and categorical features returned unchanged.
 4100:         The return type matches the input type.
 4101: 
 4102:     Examples
 4103:     --------
 4104:     >>> import numpy as np
 4105:     >>> import pandas as pd
 4106:     >>> from gofast.tools.mlutils import soft_scaler
 4107:     >>> X = np.array([[1, -1, 2], [2, 0, 0], [0, 1, -1]])
 4108:     >>> X_scaled = soft_scaler(X, kind='StandardScaler')
 4109:     >>> print(X_scaled)
 4110:     [[ 0.  -1.22474487  1.33630621]
 4111:      [ 1.22474487  0.  -0.26726124]
 4112:      [-1.22474487  1.22474487 -1.06904497]]
 4113:

If None, a new RandomForestClassifier will be trained on `X`.\n    view : bool, optional\n        If True, displays a visual summary of feature contributions using SHAP's\n        visualization tools. It is more efficient to pass a pre-trained model if \n    available.\n\n    Examples\n    --------\n    >>> from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n    >>> from gofast.tools.mlutils import get_feature_contributions\n    >>> data = load_iris()\n    >>> X = data['data']\n    >>> model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)\n    >>> model.fit(X, data['target'])\n    >>> contributions = get_feature_contributions(X, model, view=True)\n    ");

 4272:     """
 4273:     Calculate the SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) values to determine
 4274:     the contribution of each feature to the model's predictions for each
 4275:     instance in the dataset and optionally display a visual summary.
 4276: 
 4277:     Parameters
 4278:     ----------
 4279:     X : ndarray or DataFrame
 4280:         The feature matrix for which to calculate feature contributions.
 4281:     model : sklearn.base.BaseEstimator, optional
 4282:         A pre-trained tree-based machine learning model from scikit-learn (e.g.,
 4283:         RandomForest). If None, a new RandomForestClassifier will be trained on `X`.
 4284:     view : bool, optional
 4285:         If True, displays a visual summary of feature contributions using SHAP's
 4286:         visualization tools. Default is False.
 4287: 
 4288:     Returns
 4289:     -------
 4290:     ndarray
 4291:         A matrix of SHAP values where each row corresponds to an instance and
 4292:         each column corresponds to a feature's contribution to that instance's
 4293:         prediction.
 4294: 
 4295:     Notes
 4296:     -----
 4297:     The function defaults to creating and using a RandomForestClassifier if no
 4298:     model is provided. It is more efficient to pass a pre-trained model if
 4299:     available.
 4300: 
 4301:     Examples
 4302:     --------
 4303:     >>> from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
 4304:     >>> from gofast.tools.mlutils import get_feature_contributions
 4305:     >>> data = load_iris()
 4306:     >>> X = data['data']
 4307:     >>> model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
 4308:     >>> model.fit(X, data['target'])
 4309:     >>> contributions = get_feature_contributions(X, model, view=True)
 4310:     """
